I will use birthyear to count how many users are gen-z(1996-now), Millenials(1977-1995), Generation - x(1965-1976), Baby Boomers(1946-1964), Silent Generation(before-1945) then analyse that data to see how many users each generation has. The preference year is 2016.

If I use 2016 as a age preference, then Gen z, Millennials, Genx, Baby boomers, and silent generation age will range from 1-20, 21-39, 40-51, 52-70, and 71+ repectively. Millennials generation has the highest users and consider to be our main customers.

**rollout plan** Millenials take up to 70% of the total users, but gen x has only 1% of the total user other generations we will neglect because I assume that majority of people older than millennials are not incline to ride a bike due to their physical health. As for these 2 generations, they give more importance to their health than older generation and they are conservative on how they spend their money, therefore I will roll out a new promotion that for every mile they travel using bikeshare, they will get certain amount of point rewards collected into their account, which can be use to get discount for the next ride.

**success metric**  I will be using t-test metric to determine if the experiment is successful, where p-value must be less than 0.05 comparing new data of how many users have increase (at each generation) with the old data.

**secondary metric** As this promotion applies to all age, other generations might see an increase in usage, therefore we have to take into account the numbers of other generations increase or decrease.
